<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="134" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1218,1428,3037]" pageId="21" pageNumber="134">
In our view, the small Late Maastrichtian theropod (
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3396372305" collectionCode="LACM" httpUri="https://collections.nhm.org/dinosaur-institute/Display.php?irn=1032652&amp;QueryPage=%2Fdinosaur-institute%2F&amp;BackRef=ResultsList.php " pageId="21" pageNumber="134" specimenCode="LACM 28471">LACM 28471</materialsCitation>
), referred to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leidy" authorityYear="1868" box="[470,651,1560,1598]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Aublysodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="21" pageNumber="134" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Aublysodon</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Molnar, R. E. &amp; Carpenter, K." box="[721,1209,1559,1598]" firstAuthor="Molnar" journalOrPublisher="Geobios" pageId="21" pageNumber="134" pagination="445 - 454" part="22" refId="ref18439" refString="Molnar, R. E. and Carpenter, K., 1989, The Iordan theropod (Maastrichtian, Montana, U. S. A.) referred to the genus Aublysodon: Geobios, v. 22, p. 445 - 454." title="The Iordan theropod (Maastrichtian, Montana, U. S. A.) referred to the genus Aublysodon" type="journal article" year="1989">Molnar and Carpenter (1989)</bibRefCitation>
differs in no signiﬁcant way from other tyrannosaurids. The authors list several primitive features that are actually typical of juvenile tyrannosaurids (
<bibRefCitation author="Carr, T. D." box="[543,711,1691,1726]" firstAuthor="Carr" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology" pageId="21" pageNumber="134" pagination="497 - 520" part="19" refId="ref16619" refString="Carr, T. D., 1999, Craniofacial ontogeny inTyrannosauridae (Dinosauria, Theropoda): Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology, v. 19, p. 497 - 520." title="Craniofacial ontogeny inTyrannosauridae (Dinosauria, Theropoda)" type="book" year="1999">Carr, 1999</bibRefCitation>
), including long low muzzle, frontals longer than wide, smooth nasals, and a wedge-like frontoparietal suture (
<bibRefCitation author="Molnar, R. E. &amp; Carpenter, K." box="[458,929,1777,1816]" firstAuthor="Molnar" journalOrPublisher="Geobios" pageId="21" pageNumber="134" pagination="445 - 454" part="22" refId="ref18439" refString="Molnar, R. E. and Carpenter, K., 1989, The Iordan theropod (Maastrichtian, Montana, U. S. A.) referred to the genus Aublysodon: Geobios, v. 22, p. 445 - 454." title="The Iordan theropod (Maastrichtian, Montana, U. S. A.) referred to the genus Aublysodon" type="journal article" year="1989">Molnar and Carpenter, 1989</bibRefCitation>
). With regard to the diagnostic skeletal characters of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leidy" authorityYear="1868" box="[758,941,1821,1859]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Aublysodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="21" pageNumber="134" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Aublysodon</taxonomicName>
, the acute angle of the rostroventral and alveolar borders of the dentary is typical of the shallow bone in juvenile tyrannosaurids. Also, the lingually placed Carina of the first dentary tooth, different extents of the mesial and distal denticles along the tooth crown, and relatively finer mesial than distal denticles are also typical of tyrannosaurids in general (
<bibRefCitation author="Carr, T. D." bookContentInfo="358 p." box="[341,504,2085,2120]" firstAuthor="Carr" journalOrPublisher="University of Toronto, Toronto" pageId="21" pageNumber="134" refId="ref16564" refString="Carr, T. D., 1996, Cranial osteology and craniofacial ontogeny of Tyrannosauridae (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the Dinosaur Park Formation (Judith River Group, Upper Cretaceous: Campanian) of Alberta [M. S. thesis]: University of Toronto, Toronto, 358 p." title="Cranial osteology and craniofacial ontogeny of Tyrannosauridae (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the Dinosaur Park Formation (Judith River Group, Upper Cretaceous: Campanian) of Alberta" type="book" year="1996">Carr, 1996</bibRefCitation>
; Table 2). We are unsure of the signiﬁcance of the &quot;step&quot; in the alveolar border of the dentary at the third alveolus, but this region of the margin is typically convex in tyrannosaurids, and the step may simply reflect the change from a concave to a convex margin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="134" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1218,1428,3037]" pageId="21" pageNumber="134">
Finally, there is nothing in the published photographs and figures (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Molnar, R. E." box="[796,1012,2301,2335]" firstAuthor="Molnar" journalOrPublisher="Iournal of Paleontology" pageId="21" pageNumber="134" pagination="73 - 82" part="52" refId="ref18372" refString="Molnar, R. E., 1978, Anew theropod dinosaur from the Upper Cretaceous of central Montana: Iournal of Paleontology, v. 52, p. 73 - 82." title="Anew theropod dinosaur from the Upper Cretaceous of central Montana" type="book chapter" year="1978">Molnar, 1978</bibRefCitation>
) to prevent identification of 
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3396372314" box="[427,641,2346,2374]" collectionCode="LACM" httpUri="https://collections.nhm.org/dinosaur-institute/Display.php?irn=1032652&amp;QueryPage=%2Fdinosaur-institute%2F&amp;BackRef=ResultsList.php " pageId="21" pageNumber="134" specimenCode="LACM 28471">LACM 28471</materialsCitation>
as a 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1906" box="[724,1101,2345,2384]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="21" pageNumber="138" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">juvenile tyrannosaurid</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="134" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1218,1428,3037]" pageId="21" pageNumber="134">
The absence of denticles on the associated premaxillary tooth of 
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3396372312" box="[294,508,2433,2473]" collectionCode="LACM" httpUri="https://collections.nhm.org/dinosaur-institute/Display.php?irn=1032652&amp;QueryPage=%2Fdinosaur-institute%2F&amp;BackRef=ResultsList.php " pageId="21" pageNumber="134" specimenCode="LACM 28471">LACM 24871</materialsCitation>
, generally small size of &quot; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leidy" authorityYear="1868" box="[922,1104,2432,2470]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Aublysodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="21" pageNumber="134" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Aublysodon</taxonomicName>
&quot; teeth, et. (
<bibRefCitation author="Currie, PJ &amp; Rigby, JK. Jr. &amp; Sloan, RE" box="[170,468,2476,2510]" editor="Carpenter, K. &amp; Currie, PJ." etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Currie" journalOrPublisher="Cambridge, Cambridge University Press" pageId="21" pageNumber="134" pagination="107 - 125" refId="ref16971" refString="Currie, PJ., Rigby, JK. Jr. and Sloan, RE., 1990, Theropod teeth from the Judith River Formation; in Carpenter, K. and Currie, PJ., eds., Dinosaur Systematics: Cambridge, Cambridge University Press, p. 107 - 125." title="Theropod teeth from the Judith River Formation" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Dinosaur Systematics" year="1990">Currie et al., 1990</bibRefCitation>
), and widespread geographic and temporal occurrence (
<bibRefCitation author="Currie, PJ &amp; Rigby, JK. Jr. &amp; Sloan, RE" box="[357,637,2520,2554]" editor="Carpenter, K. &amp; Currie, PJ." etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Currie" journalOrPublisher="Cambridge, Cambridge University Press" pageId="21" pageNumber="134" pagination="107 - 125" refId="ref16971" refString="Currie, PJ., Rigby, JK. Jr. and Sloan, RE., 1990, Theropod teeth from the Judith River Formation; in Carpenter, K. and Currie, PJ., eds., Dinosaur Systematics: Cambridge, Cambridge University Press, p. 107 - 125." title="Theropod teeth from the Judith River Formation" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Dinosaur Systematics" year="1990">Currie et al., 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Eaton, J. G. &amp; Diem, S. &amp; Archibald, J. D. &amp; Schierup, C. &amp; Munk, H." box="[655,938,2520,2553]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Eaton" journalOrPublisher="Utah Geological Survey, Miscellaneous Publication" pageId="21" pageNumber="134" pagination="323 - 353" part="99 - 1" refId="ref17081" refString="Eaton, J. G., Diem, S., Archibald, J. D., Schierup, C. and Munk, H., 1999 a, Vertebrate paleontology of the Upper Cretaceous Rocks of the Markagunt Plateau, southwestern Utah: Utah Geological Survey, Miscellaneous Publication 99 - 1, p. p. 323 - 353" title="Vertebrate paleontology of the Upper Cretaceous Rocks of the Markagunt Plateau, southwestern Utah" type="book" year="1999" yearSuffix="a">Eaton et al. 1999a</bibRefCitation>
,b; 
<bibRefCitation author="Parrish, J. M." box="[984,1195,2520,2553]" firstAuthor="Parrish" journalOrPublisher="Utah Geological Survey, Miscellaneous Publication" pageId="21" pageNumber="134" pagination="329 - 321" part="99 - 1" refId="ref18729" refString="Parrish, J. M., 1999, Dinosaur teeth from the Upper Cretaceous (Turonian-Judithian) of southern Utah: Utah Geological Survey, Miscellaneous Publication 99 - 1, p. 329 - 321." title="Dinosaur teeth from the Upper Cretaceous (Turonian-Judithian) of southern Utah" type="book" year="1999">Parrish, 1999</bibRefCitation>
), strongly suggests that a lack of denticles reflects relative development, as in other coelurosaurs such as velociraptorine dromaeosaurids. Pending personal examination of the fossil, we consider the specimen to represent a juvenile indeterminate tyrannosaurid.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
